result.execSummary:
The defendant Shane M Blankenship was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).
  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Atty Hendee states plea agreement to counts 1, 2 & 3 in 15CF8 and Ct. 2 in 14CM149.  Ct. 4 in 15CF8 & Ct. 1 in 14CM149 to be dismissed and read-in.  Atty Hendee states that parties will be requesting a sentencing date be set 30 days out.  Atty Hendee states that parties stipulate that the bond will be amended to a signature bond with added conditions. If defendant does not violate the bond in any way prior to the sentencing in this case, the State wont object to the defendant withdrawing his plea on that charge and then the State will move to dismiss and read in the charge for sentencing purposes.  However, if there are any violations of bond prior to sentencing, the parties agree that the Court can sentence defendant on the Strangulation charge and the State is not bound by the following agreement and can argue for prison.
Atty Johnson agrees.  Court questions the defendant.  Defendant agrees and enters a No Contest pleas.
  Court questions defendant regarding plea. Advises of Constitutional Rights and elements of the charge.  Court finds plea made knowingly, voluntarily & Intelligently.

  BY THE COURT:  Court finds a sufficient factual basis to support the charges.  Court accepts defendant's plea and finds defendant guilty of Counts 1, 2 & 3 in 15CF8 and Ct. 2 in 14CM149.  Ct. 4 in 15CF8 & Ct. 1 in 14CM149 to be dismissed and read-in.

Atty Hendee states that since the defendant has not been sentenced yet; the State requests that the bond conditions and the added bond conditions be continued until that sentencing date.
Atty Johnson agrees with the State and states that his client is taking responsibility in the matter and would appreciate the bond being amended to a signature bond.
Atty Hendee asks that the previous conditions be modified to the bond conditions that he stated.


BY THE COURT:  Court will amend the cash bond to a $1,000 Signature bond with conditions:
*No contact with Haley Harris in any form, in person, in writing, telephonically, electronically or otherwise  EXCEPT through his mother for the express purposes of child visitation or return of property
*Absolute sobriety and no possession of any controlled substance without a valid prescription
*The defendant shall be subject to random urine analysis testing at the discretion of the District Attorney to be coordinated with his counsel.  The testing shall be completed within 48 hours from the request.
*The defendant shall not dispose of, destroy, or otherwise alter any property within or surrounding the residence owned by or jointly owned with Haley Harris without further Court order.

BY THE COURT:  Set for Sentencing.
